        "body": "<!--ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…\r\n\r\nOh hi there! ðŸ˜„ \r\n\r\nTo expedite issue processing please search open and closed issues before submitting a new one.\r\nExisting issues often contain information about workarounds, resolution, or progress updates.\r\n\r\nðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…ðŸ”…-->\r\n\r\n\r\n# ðŸš€ feature request\r\n\r\n### Relevant Package\r\n@angular/router\r\n\r\n\r\n### Description\r\nI want to keep the parent child relationship in the routes (because I am using it for the breadcrumbs) in the application, but I want the child to be loaded in the router-outlet where the parent is mounted.\r\n\r\nExample issue:\r\nhttps://stackblitz.com/edit/angular-bpga5a?file=src%2Fapp%2Fapp.component.html\r\n\r\n### Describe the solution you'd like\r\nIf I used outlet name for the child, and assign it to the router outlet where the parent is mounted, then it should work\r\n\r\n### Describe alternatives you've considered\r\n<!-- âœï¸--> Have you considered any alternative solutions or workarounds?\r\n"
